<BlogLayout
  title="Why AI Coding Tools Waste 90% of Your Tokens"
  description="AI coding assistants send thousands of redundant tokens per interaction. Here's why it happens and how lean-ctx fixes it."
  date="2026-03-19"
>
  <p>
    If you use Cursor, GitHub Copilot, Claude Code, or any AI coding assistant, you're
    burning through tokens at an alarming rate. Most of those tokens are wasted on information
    the LLM already has in its context window.
  </p>

  <h2>The Problem: Redundant Context</h2>

  <p>
    When you ask your AI assistant to edit a file, here's what typically happens:
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li>The tool reads the full file into context (let's say 915 tokens for <code>auth.ts</code>)</li>
    <li>The LLM processes your request and makes changes</li>
    <li>You ask a follow-up question about the same file</li>
    <li>The tool reads the <strong>entire file again</strong> — another 915 tokens</li>
    <li>Repeat for every interaction</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    In a typical 30-minute session, you might read the same file 5-10 times. That's
    <strong>4,500-9,000 tokens</strong> for a single file. Multiply by the 10-20 files
    in a typical context window, and you're looking at <strong>50,000-100,000 wasted tokens
    per session</strong>.
  </p>

  <h2>The Real Numbers</h2>

  <p>
    We benchmarked lean-ctx on a real production project (<code>thinkery.ch</code>) using
    tiktoken for exact measurements:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>auth.ts</strong> (123 lines): 915 tokens per read. After caching: 13 tokens. Savings: <strong>99%</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Dependency API surface:</strong> 2,536 tokens → 252 tokens with signature extraction. Savings: <strong>90%</strong></li>
    <li><strong>npm install output:</strong> 284 tokens → 42 tokens. Savings: <strong>85%</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Project tree:</strong> 980 tokens → 588 tokens. Savings: <strong>40%</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Why Existing Solutions Fall Short</h2>

  <p>
    Tools like RTK focus only on shell output compression. That helps, but shell output is
    a fraction of total token usage. The biggest waste comes from <strong>file re-reads</strong>
    — which no other tool addresses.
  </p>

  <p>
    OrbitalMCP offers some context optimization but achieves only 20-25% savings and works
    exclusively with Cursor.
  </p>

  <h2>The lean-ctx Approach</h2>

  <p>
    lean-ctx takes a fundamentally different approach. Instead of trying to compress everything
    uniformly, it uses <strong>domain-specific strategies</strong> for each type of context:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Session caching:</strong> Files are read once and cached with MD5 hashes. Re-reads return a 13-token "already in context" message</li>
    <li><strong>Signature extraction:</strong> For dependency files, only function signatures, interfaces, and types are sent — 87% fewer tokens while preserving the API surface</li>
    <li><strong>Diff-based updates:</strong> When a cached file changes, only the changed lines are sent</li>
    <li><strong>Compact protocol:</strong> Type abbreviations (<code>:s</code> for string), async markers (<code>&#8859;</code>), and file references (<code>F1</code>) reduce boilerplate</li>
    <li><strong>Pattern compression:</strong> CLI output from npm, git, docker, and tsc is compressed using tool-specific patterns</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The Impact</h2>

  <p>
    In our validation sessions, lean-ctx consistently achieves <strong>77-99% token reduction</strong>.
    For heavy users on paid API plans, that translates directly to cost savings. For users on
    rate-limited plans (like Cursor Pro), it means <strong>more interactions before hitting the limit</strong>.
  </p>

  <h2>Getting Started</h2>

  <p>
    lean-ctx is open source (MIT license) and takes 2 minutes to set up. It works as an MCP server
    with Cursor, GitHub Copilot, Claude Code, and Windsurf.
  </p>

